The paper deals with the problem of generating quasi-Gray codes, which is a topic in discrete mathematics and theoretical computer science. The paper discusses the number of bits read and written at each generating step, the average number of bits read while generating the entire code, and the number of strings generated in the code, which are all topics in algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also presents trade-offs between these constraints, which is a topic in combinatorics (cs.DM). The paper uses information theory to analyze the efficiency of the algorithms, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the use of graphs to represent the quasi-Gray codes, which is a topic in computational complexity (cs.CC) and numerical analysis (cs.NA).
